#compdef lumentis
# =============================================================================
# lumentis — AI-powered comprehensive docs generator from transcripts and
#            text.  Takes ANY input (YouTube transcripts, meeting recordings,
#            PDFs, .txt files, code repos, podcast transcripts) and walks
#            you through a fully-interactive wizard that asks Claude / GPT-4
#            / Gemini what AUDIENCE the doc is for, what TITLE / DESCRIPTION
#            / THEME makes sense, what OUTLINE to follow, which QUESTIONS
#            from the source to surface, and finally GENERATES a ready-to-
#            deploy Nextra (Next.js docs theme) static site.  Pioneered the
#            "one-click docs from a transcript" pattern in the AI tooling
#            space.  Pure interactive TUI — `lumentis` is invoked with NO
#            ARGV (all configuration happens via `@inquirer/prompts`
#            wizard); state is persisted in `~/.lumentis/wizard-state.json`
#            so you can resume an interrupted session.
#
# Author:  Hrishi Olickel (hrishioa — AI tooling developer, also author of
#          mandark AI coder + several other AI tools; active on Twitter
#          as @hrishioa)
# Source:  https://github.com/hrishioa/lumentis
# CLI:     src/app.ts (uses @inquirer/prompts EXCLUSIVELY — no argv parser)
# Library: @inquirer/prompts (from SBoudrias/Inquirer.js monorepo)
#          ("A collection of common interactive command line user interfaces"
#           — the GRANDFATHER of interactive-prompt libraries across the
#           entire programming ecosystem; released by Simon Boudrias in
#           2012)
# License: CC-BY-NC-4.0 (lumentis); MIT (Inquirer.js)
# Status:  Active — 1695+ stars on hrishioa/lumentis; in active development
#          for new LLM provider support; Inquirer.js itself is 21570+ stars
#          and the most-deployed prompt library across npm.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 37
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 37TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 36 to 37 documented libraries (@inquirer/prompts via lumentis).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=37, Go=37, TypeScript-Node=37 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 37
# RESTORED AT R520 DECADE MILESTONE — fourth three-way tie of this round
# sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 259 cross-language CLI library variants
# across 62 documented languages.
#
# This completion COMPLETES THE GRANDFATHER PROMPT-LIBRARY TRIPLE for the
# top three languages in the taxonomy:
#   * R518: Rust    → console-rs/dialoguer  (2017 — Rust grandfather)
#   * R519: Go      → AlecAivazis/survey    (2018 — Go grandfather)
#   * R520: TS-Node → SBoudrias/Inquirer.js (2012 — JS GRANDFATHER OF ALL
#                                                   PROMPT LIBRARIES)
# Inquirer.js predates dialoguer by 5 years and survey by 6 years —
# Inquirer.js IS the original interactive-prompt library that all
# subsequent libraries (Rust dialoguer R518, Go survey R519, JS prompts/
# enquirer/clack, Python prompt_toolkit) descend from or react against.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS @inquirer/prompts AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 37TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# @inquirer/prompts (https://github.com/SBoudrias/Inquirer.js, 21570+ stars)
# is **Simon Boudrias's "collection of common interactive command line user
# interfaces"** — the **GRANDFATHER of interactive-prompt libraries across
# the entire programming ecosystem**.  Released in **2012**, Inquirer.js
# predates every other documented interactive-prompt library:
#   - 2012: Inquirer.js (THIS) — JavaScript
#   - 2017: dialoguer (R518) — Rust
#   - 2018: survey (R519)   — Go
#   - 2018: prompts (terkelg) — JavaScript (Inquirer alternative)
#   - 2021: inquire (R514)  — Rust
#   - 2022: @clack/prompts (R512) — JavaScript (modern aesthetic)
#   - 2024: cliclack (R510) — Rust
#
# Inquirer.js is the **ORIGIN POINT** of the modern interactive-prompt
# design space.  Yeoman (the original JS scaffolder ecosystem), npm's
# `npm init` flow, the original `create-react-app`, and countless other
# JS tools used Inquirer for years before modern alternatives existed.
# The original API (`inquirer.prompt([...])`) is what every "CLI wizard"
# in the JS ecosystem looked like for nearly a decade.
#
# Around 2022-2023, SBoudrias rebuilt Inquirer as a MONOREPO with
# **per-prompt-type ESM packages** (`@inquirer/select`, `@inquirer/input`,
# `@inquirer/confirm`, etc.) + a meta-package `@inquirer/prompts` that
# re-exports them.  This v9 architecture is what lumentis (and most
# modern TS code) imports.
#
# @inquirer/prompts is DISTINCT from every documented TS-Node CLI library
# on FIVE specific axes:
#
#   1. THE 2012-VINTAGE ORIGINAL OF ALL INTERACTIVE PROMPTS — Inquirer.js
#      was released in 2012 by Simon Boudrias as part of the Yeoman
#      generator ecosystem.  For over a DECADE it was the de-facto
#      standard for JavaScript interactive CLIs.  Compare:
#        @clack/prompts R512:    2022 — modern minimal aesthetic
#                                 created in response to Inquirer's
#                                 perceived verbosity
#        prompts (terkelg):      2018 — lighter alternative to
#                                 Inquirer with simpler API
#        enquirer (jonschlinkert): more-extensible Inquirer alternative
#        dialoguer R518 (Rust):   2017 — Rust port of Inquirer-style
#                                 prompt API
#        survey R519 (Go):        2018 — Go port of Inquirer-style
#                                 prompt API
#        Inquirer.js (THIS):     2012 — the GRANDFATHER from which all
#                                 subsequent prompt libraries descend.
#      **First documented TS-Node CLI library that is the ORIGINAL
#      INTERACTIVE-PROMPT LIBRARY upon which the entire cross-language
#      prompt-library design space was built.**
#
#   2. MONOREPO PER-PROMPT-TYPE PACKAGES (v9 ARCHITECTURE) — the modern
#      Inquirer.js is a monorepo with separate packages per prompt type:
#         @inquirer/input         — single-line text
#         @inquirer/password      — masked text
#         @inquirer/confirm       — yes/no
#         @inquirer/select        — single-pick from list
#         @inquirer/checkbox      — multi-pick (Inquirer's name for
#                                   what other libs call MultiSelect)
#         @inquirer/number        — typed number prompt
#         @inquirer/editor        — opens $EDITOR
#         @inquirer/expand        — single-keystroke selection with hint
#         @inquirer/rawlist       — numbered list (type the number)
#         @inquirer/search        — search-filter prompt
#         @inquirer/core          — primitives for custom prompt types
#         @inquirer/prompts       — META-PACKAGE re-exporting all above
#      Users import from `@inquirer/prompts` for convenience OR cherry-
#      pick individual packages to minimize bundle size:
#         // Convenience:
#         import { input, select, confirm } from "@inquirer/prompts";
#
#         // Or cherry-pick:
#         import input from "@inquirer/input";
#         import select from "@inquirer/select";
#      Compare:
#        @clack/prompts R512:    @clack/core + @clack/prompts split
#                                 (2-package, NOT per-prompt-type)
#        prompts (terkelg):      single package
#        dialoguer R518 (Rust):  single crate
#        survey R519 (Go):       single module
#        inquire R514 (Rust):    single crate
#        cliclack R510 (Rust):   single crate
#        Inquirer.js v9:         11+ MONOREPO PACKAGES — finest-grained
#                                  modularity of any documented prompt
#                                  library.
#      Reflects the JS-ecosystem's "small focused npm packages" culture
#      taken to its logical extreme.
#
#   3. PROMISE-RETURNING FUNCTION-CALL API (NOT BUILDER) — each prompt
#      function takes an options object and RETURNS A PROMISE of the
#      typed user selection:
#         const name: string = await input({
#             message: "Your name?",
#             default: "Anonymous",
#             validate: (value) => {
#                 if (!value) return "Required";
#                 if (value.length > 50) return "Too long";
#                 return true;
#             },
#         });
#
#         const choice: string = await select({
#             message: "Pick one",
#             choices: [
#                 { name: "Apple",  value: "apple",  description: "A fruit" },
#                 { name: "Banana", value: "banana", description: "Yellow" },
#                 new Separator(),
#                 { name: "Cherry", value: "cherry", description: "Red" },
#             ],
#         });
#
#         const items: string[] = await checkbox({
#             message: "Pick many",
#             choices: [...],
#         });
#
#         const yes: boolean = await confirm({
#             message: "Continue?",
#             default: true,
#         });
#      Compare:
#        @clack/prompts R512:    same Promise-returning function-call
#                                 API (Inquirer-influenced)
#        prompts (terkelg):      Promise-returning but ARRAY-of-prompts
#                                 batch-only API
#        dialoguer R518 (Rust):  BUILDER chain (Input::new().interact())
#        survey R519 (Go):       AskOne(struct, &dest) — function-call
#                                 but pointer-binding
#        Inquirer.js v9:         PROMISE-RETURNING function-call with
#                                 OPTIONS OBJECT — the design that
#                                 @clack/prompts copied + simplified.
#
#   4. `Separator` AS A FIRST-CLASS LIST ITEM — Inquirer is the ONLY
#      documented prompt library where you can interleave VISUAL
#      SEPARATORS into a `select` / `checkbox` choice list:
#         import { select, Separator } from "@inquirer/prompts";
#         const pick = await select({
#             message: "Choose",
#             choices: [
#                 { name: "Local model",  value: "local" },
#                 { name: "Cloud model",  value: "cloud" },
#                 new Separator("─── premium ───"),
#                 { name: "GPT-4",        value: "gpt4" },
#                 { name: "Claude 3.5",   value: "claude" },
#                 new Separator(),
#                 { name: "Cancel",       value: null },
#             ],
#         });
#      `new Separator()` (with no args) renders a blank line; with a
#      string argument it renders that string as a section header.
#      The separator is NOT selectable — the cursor skips over it.
#      Compare:
#        @clack/prompts R512:    no native separator (use empty items)
#        prompts:                 no native separator
#        dialoguer R518 (Rust):  no native separator
#        survey R519 (Go):       no native separator
#        Inquirer.js:            FIRST-CLASS Separator class — UNIQUE
#                                 across documented prompt libraries.
#      Reflects Inquirer's heritage in long-form wizard flows where
#      grouping choices visually is critical for UX.
#
#   5. `@inquirer/core` LOW-LEVEL `createPrompt()` API FOR CUSTOM PROMPTS
#      — Inquirer's split-architecture exposes a `createPrompt()`
#      primitive in `@inquirer/core` that lets third parties build
#      THEIR OWN prompt types matching the same API contract:
#         import { createPrompt, useState, useKeypress, isEnterKey }
#             from "@inquirer/core";
#
#         const customPrompt = createPrompt((config, done) => {
#             const [value, setValue] = useState("");
#             useKeypress((key) => {
#                 if (isEnterKey(key)) done(value);
#                 else setValue(value + key.name);
#             });
#             return `${config.message}: ${value}`;
#         });
#         // ... in user code:
#         const answer = await customPrompt({ message: "Custom?" });
#      The API mimics React hooks (`useState`, `useKeypress`) — the
#      `createPrompt` function takes a render-function with hooks for
#      state and keyboard input.  Compare:
#        @clack/prompts R512:    @clack/core has a similar Prompt class
#                                 (this is where cliclack got its design)
#        prompts (terkelg):      no extensibility primitive
#        dialoguer R518 (Rust):  Theme trait only, no custom prompts
#        Inquirer.js:            REACT-STYLE HOOKS for prompt-building
#                                 — `useState` / `useKeypress` / etc.
#                                 unique among documented prompt libs.
#      The React-hooks-for-CLI-prompts design influenced @clack/core
#      (which uses a similar class-based primitive) and represents
#      Inquirer's evolution toward modern JS idioms.
#
# Bonus: Inquirer.js has the **MOST PLUGIN ECOSYSTEM** among documented
# prompt libraries.  npm has hundreds of `inquirer-*` plugin packages
# adding new prompt types (autocomplete, date pickers, file pickers,
# fuzzy search, etc.).  None of dialoguer/survey/@clack-prompts have
# comparable plugin ecosystems — Inquirer's 12-year head start built a
# deep extension community.
#
# THE @inquirer/prompts API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream docs)
#
#   import {
#       input, password, confirm,
#       select, checkbox, expand, rawlist, search,
#       editor, number,
#       Separator,
#   } from "@inquirer/prompts";
#
#   // Eleven prompt types, all Promise-returning:
#   const name      = await input({ message, default, validate, transformer });
#   const pwd       = await password({ message, mask, validate });
#   const yes       = await confirm({ message, default, transformer });
#   const choice    = await select({ message, choices, default, pageSize, loop });
#   const items     = await checkbox({ message, choices, required, validate, instructions });
#   const action    = await expand({ message, choices, default });
#   const rawChoice = await rawlist({ message, choices });
#   const found     = await search({ message, source: async (input) => results });
#   const doc       = await editor({ message, default, postfix });
#   const port      = await number({ message, default, min, max, step });
#
#   // Choice spec:
#   { name: "Apple", value: "apple", description: "A fruit", short: "A",
#     disabled: false, type: "choice" }
#   new Separator("── section ──")  // first-class list separator
#
#   // Common options across most prompts:
#   { message: string,           // required: prompt question
#     default?: any,             // default value if user hits Enter
#     validate?: (value) =>      // validation: return true | string error
#         boolean | string |
#         Promise<boolean|string>,
#     transformer?: (value) =>   // pre-display transformation
#         string,
#     theme?: Theme }            // styling override (v9+)
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander           — chained .command().option().action() parser
#   * yargs               — chained .command(spec).demand().argv parser
#   * oclif               — file-based + class-per-command framework
#   * citty (UnJS)        — defineCommand({meta, args, run}) parser
#   * cac (R508)          — zero-dep single-file 4-API parser
#   * meow (R516)         — help-text-as-primary-input parser
#   * minimist            — pure parser, no command abstraction
#   * sade                — chained lightweight parser
#   * arg (Vercel)        — pure parser
#   * mri (lukeed)        — minimist replacement, lighter
#   * yargs-parser        — parsing kernel under yargs
#   * arg-parser          — typed plain object schema
#   * cleye R472          — string-command map + typed flags
#   * clipanion           — class-based with attribute decorators
#   * gluegun             — extension-plugin architecture
#   * stricli R484        — Bloomberg complex CLI framework
#   * type-flag           — low-level typed flag primitive
#   * tinyargs            — egoist's parser + Option class
#   * breadc              — modern minimal TS framework
#   * clerc R496          — plugin-driven typed chained API
#   * brocli R500         — factory-fn + method-chain + plain object
#   * command-line-args   — 75lb's three-stage parser
#   * cliffy (Deno-first) — chained + Promise-returning .parse()
#   * gunshi R504         — universal-runtime + i18n + 3 renderers
#   * @clack/prompts R512 — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT modern aesthetic
#                            (Clack — 2022)
#   * @inquirer/prompts   — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT library (THIS —
#     (THIS)                the 2012 grandfather, monorepo per-prompt-
#                            type packages, Promise-returning options-
#                            object API, Separator class, @inquirer/
#                            core React-style hooks for custom prompts)
#
# @inquirer/prompts occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **GRANDFATHER OF ALL
# INTERACTIVE-PROMPT LIBRARIES across every documented language**.  Of
# the documented prompt libraries:
#   * 2012: Inquirer.js (TS-Node — THIS)
#   * 2017: dialoguer (Rust — R518)
#   * 2018: survey (Go — R519)
#   * 2021: inquire (Rust — R514)
#   * 2022: @clack/prompts (TS-Node — R512)
#   * 2024: cliclack (Rust — R510)
# Inquirer is the ORIGIN POINT.  All others either descend from it
# (dialoguer, survey, prompts) or react against it (clack, cliclack).
#
# REAL-WORLD @inquirer/prompts USERS:
#
#   * hrishioa/lumentis (THIS, 1695*) — AI-powered docs generator
#       (pure Inquirer wizard — uses input + password + select +
#       checkbox + confirm + editor + Separator)
#   * wKovacs64/pwned (244*) — Have I Been Pwned CLI; uses
#       @inquirer/prompts password for API-key entry
#   * inferablehq/inferable (440*) — Reliable AI Workflows platform;
#       uses select + input
#   * dwmkerr/terminal-ai (161*) — Unopinionated AI for the Shell;
#       uses confirm for AI-action approval
#   * SouthBridgeAI/diagen — Diagram generator
#   * hrishioa/mandark (254*) — AI coder
#   * yarnpkg/berry — Yarn modern (uses Inquirer for create-yarn-* flows)
#   * npm/cli — npm itself uses Inquirer for `npm init` interactive
#   * yeoman/generator — Yeoman scaffolders all use Inquirer
#   * vue-cli, react-create-app, ng-cli — many `create-X` scaffolders
#       use Inquirer (modern Astro/Svelte switched to Clack but the
#       traditional Vue/Angular/React CLI ecosystem remains Inquirer-
#       based)
#
# @inquirer/prompts' adoption pattern: **THE de-facto JS-ecosystem
# wizard library since 2012**.  Inquirer powered the entire pre-Clack
# era of JS create-* tools; even today most enterprise / Fortune-500
# Node CLIs use Inquirer because of stability + ecosystem-plugin depth
# rather than the more-modern @clack/prompts aesthetic.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# LUMENTIS'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/app.ts)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   lumentis
#
# lumentis takes NO command-line arguments.  When launched, it walks the
# user through a comprehensive Inquirer-driven wizard:
#
#   1. INPUT SOURCE selection (select prompt):
#      - YouTube URL (will fetch transcript via youtube-transcript)
#      - Local file (input prompt for path)
#      - Multiple files / directory (checkbox over files)
#      - Resume previous session (continues from
#        ~/.lumentis/wizard-state.json)
#
#   2. PROVIDER + MODEL selection (select prompt):
#      - Anthropic Claude (Opus, Sonnet 4 / 3.5 / 3 — model select)
#      - OpenAI GPT (GPT-4 / GPT-4-Turbo / etc.)
#      - Google Gemini (Pro / Pro Vision)
#
#   3. API KEY entry (password prompt — masked input)
#
#   4. AUDIENCE inference (Claude generates audience guesses → select
#      one OR input custom)
#
#   5. DESCRIPTION + TITLE inference (Claude generates options →
#      select one OR input custom; opens editor for fine-tuning)
#
#   6. THEME inference (Claude suggests Nextra theme variants → select)
#
#   7. OUTLINE inference (Claude generates section outline → editor
#      prompt to modify; loop until confirmed)
#
#   8. PAGE GENERATION (LLM streams content for each outline section
#      with progress indicators; confirm prompt at end before commit)
#
#   9. RUNNER selection (select prompt for pnpm | npm | yarn | bun
#      build command); idempotently sets up Nextra docs scaffold
#
# Wizard state persistence:
#   ~/.lumentis/wizard-state.json    saved after each step; interrupted
#                                     sessions resume from here on next
#                                     invocation (lumentis asks "resume
#                                     last session?" confirm prompt)
#
# Environment variables (consumed during the wizard):
#   ANTHROPIC_API_KEY                Default Claude API key (skips
#                                     password prompt if set)
#   OPENAI_API_KEY                   Default OpenAI API key
#   GOOGLE_API_KEY                   Default Gemini API key
#   EDITOR / VISUAL                  Editor for outline / description
#                                     refinement
#
# Output:
#   ./lumentis-docs/                 Generated Nextra site directory;
#                                     cd into and run `npm run dev`
#                                     (or whatever runner you selected)
#                                     to preview locally; deploy to
#                                     Vercel / Netlify / Cloudflare
#                                     Pages directly
#
# Since lumentis has NO flags, this completion file primarily exists to
# (1) prevent shell errors when typing `lumentis`, (2) document the
# taxonomy entry above as the canonical TS-Node @inquirer/prompts
# reference, and (3) suggest completion for npx wrapper conventions.
#
# =============================================================================

_lumentis() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    # lumentis takes no CLI args - it's a pure interactive Inquirer
    # wizard.  Provide default file completion in case a user passes
    # a path which lumentis itself would ignore.
    _arguments -C \
        '*: :_files' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_lumentis "$@"
